        "Getting Started with PHP",
        "PHP is a popular server-side scripting language designed for web development. It powers millions of websites including WordPress, Facebook, and Wikipedia.\n\nPHP stands for \"PHP: Hypertext Preprocessor\" and has been a cornerstone of web development since its creation in 1994 by Rasmus Lerdorf. What started as a simple set of Common Gateway Interface (CGI) binaries written in C has evolved into a full-featured programming language.\n\nWhy Choose PHP?\n\nPHP remains one of the most widely used server-side languages for several compelling reasons. First, it has an extremely low barrier to entry — you can embed PHP directly into HTML, making it intuitive for beginners. Second, it boasts an enormous ecosystem of frameworks like Laravel, Symfony, and CodeIgniter that accelerate development. Third, virtually every web hosting provider supports PHP out of the box.\n\nSetting Up Your Environment\n\nTo get started, you will need a local development environment. Popular options include XAMPP (cross-platform), WAMP (Windows), and MAMP (macOS). These bundles include Apache, MySQL, and PHP pre-configured and ready to use. Simply install one, place your .php files in the htdocs directory, and navigate to localhost in your browser.\n\nYour First PHP Script\n\nCreate a file called hello.php and add: &lt;?php echo 'Hello, World!'; ?&gt;. When you open this in your browser through your local server, you will see the greeting displayed. From here, you can explore variables, arrays, loops, functions, and object-oriented programming to build increasingly complex applications.",
