        "JavaScript Async/Await Explained",
        "Async/await is syntactic sugar built on top of Promises. It makes asynchronous code look and behave like synchronous code, making it much easier to read and maintain.\n\nThe Problem with Callbacks\n\nBefore Promises and async/await, JavaScript developers relied on callbacks to handle asynchronous operations. This often led to deeply nested code known as \"callback hell\" — where each asynchronous operation required another nested function, making the code difficult to read, debug, and maintain.\n\nPromises: A Step Forward\n\nPromises introduced a cleaner way to handle async operations by representing a value that might be available now, in the future, or never. With .then() and .catch() chaining, code became more linear. However, complex flows with multiple dependent async calls could still become hard to follow.\n\nEnter Async/Await\n\nThe async keyword before a function declaration makes it return a Promise automatically. Inside an async function, you can use the await keyword to pause execution until a Promise resolves. This makes the code read top-to-bottom, just like synchronous code.\n\nFor example:\nasync function fetchUserData() {\n  const response = await fetch('/api/user');\n  const data = await response.json();\n  return data;\n}\n\nError Handling\n\nWith async/await, you can use familiar try/catch blocks for error handling instead of .catch() chains. This makes error handling more intuitive and consistent with how you handle errors in synchronous code.\n\nBest Practices\n\nAlways handle errors with try/catch. Use Promise.all() when you need to run multiple independent async operations in parallel rather than sequentially. Avoid using await inside loops when the iterations are independent — instead, map to an array of Promises and await them all at once.",
