        "Introduction to MySQL Databases",
        "MySQL is an open-source relational database management system. It uses SQL (Structured Query Language) to manage data and is one of the most popular databases for web applications.\n\nWhat is a Relational Database?\n\nA relational database organizes data into tables (also called relations) consisting of rows and columns. Each table represents an entity (like users, products, or orders), and relationships between tables are established through foreign keys. This structure ensures data integrity and allows powerful querying capabilities.\n\nMySQL History and Adoption\n\nMySQL was created in 1995 by MySQL AB and is now owned by Oracle Corporation. It is the database behind some of the world's largest applications, including Facebook, Twitter, YouTube, and Netflix. Its open-source nature, reliability, and performance have made it the default choice for countless web applications.\n\nCore Concepts\n\nDatabases contain tables. Tables have columns (fields) with defined data types like INT, VARCHAR, TEXT, DATE, and BOOLEAN. Rows represent individual records. Primary keys uniquely identify each row, while foreign keys create relationships between tables.\n\nEssential SQL Commands\n\nCREATE TABLE defines a new table structure. INSERT INTO adds new records. SELECT retrieves data with powerful filtering using WHERE, JOIN, GROUP BY, and ORDER BY clauses. UPDATE modifies existing records, and DELETE removes them.\n\nIndexing and Performance\n\nIndexes dramatically speed up data retrieval by creating optimized lookup structures. Always index columns used in WHERE clauses and JOIN conditions. However, indexes slow down write operations, so use them judiciously. Understanding the EXPLAIN command helps you analyze and optimize query performance.\n\nSecurity Considerations\n\nNever concatenate user input directly into SQL queries — this leads to SQL injection vulnerabilities. Always use prepared statements with parameterized queries. Limit database user privileges to only what is necessary, and keep MySQL updated to the latest stable version.",
