        "Understanding DOM Manipulation",
        "The Document Object Model (DOM) is a programming interface for web documents. JavaScript can access and change all elements of an HTML document through the DOM, enabling dynamic and interactive web pages.\n\nWhat is the DOM?\n\nWhen a browser loads an HTML page, it creates a tree-like representation of the document in memory called the DOM. Every HTML element becomes a node in this tree, with parent-child relationships matching the nesting of HTML tags. JavaScript can traverse this tree, read element properties, modify content, change styles, and respond to user interactions.\n\nSelecting Elements\n\nModern JavaScript provides several methods to select elements: document.getElementById() for selecting by ID, document.querySelector() for CSS-selector-based selection of a single element, and document.querySelectorAll() for selecting multiple elements. querySelector and querySelectorAll are the most versatile, accepting any valid CSS selector.\n\nModifying Content and Attributes\n\nUse element.textContent to change text content (safe from XSS) or element.innerHTML to set HTML content (be cautious with user input). Modify attributes with element.setAttribute(), element.getAttribute(), and element.removeAttribute(). Access data attributes through the element.dataset property.\n\nManipulating Styles and Classes\n\nChange inline styles directly: element.style.backgroundColor = 'blue'. For better separation of concerns, toggle CSS classes using element.classList.add(), .remove(), .toggle(), and .contains(). This approach keeps styling in CSS where it belongs.\n\nCreating and Removing Elements\n\nCreate new elements with document.createElement(), set their properties, then insert them using parent.appendChild(), parent.insertBefore(), or the modern parent.append() and element.before()/after() methods. Remove elements with element.remove() or parent.removeChild().\n\nEvent Handling\n\nThe DOM event system is crucial for interactivity. Use element.addEventListener() to respond to clicks, form submissions, keyboard input, mouse movements, and hundreds of other events. Understanding event bubbling, capturing, and delegation patterns is essential for building efficient, maintainable event handling in complex applications.\n\nPerformance Considerations\n\nDOM manipulation is one of the most expensive operations in JavaScript. Minimize reflows and repaints by batching DOM updates, using DocumentFragment for multiple insertions, and leveraging requestAnimationFrame for visual updates. Consider virtual DOM libraries for highly dynamic interfaces.",
