        "PHP and MySQL Best Practices",
        "Writing secure and efficient PHP code that interacts with MySQL requires following established best practices. This guide covers the essential patterns every developer should know.\n\nAlways Use Prepared Statements\n\nThe single most important practice is to never concatenate user input into SQL queries. SQL injection is one of the most common and devastating web vulnerabilities. Use prepared statements with parameterized queries — whether with PDO or MySQLi. Prepared statements separate SQL logic from data, making injection attacks impossible.\n\nExample with PDO:\n\$stmt = \$pdo->prepare('SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = :email');\n\$stmt->execute(['email' => \$userInput]);\n\nInput Validation and Sanitization\n\nValidate all input on the server side, regardless of client-side validation. Use filter_var() for common validations like email addresses, URLs, and integers. Sanitize output with htmlspecialchars() to prevent Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks. Never trust user input — validate type, length, format, and range.\n\nError Handling\n\nSet PDO to throw exceptions: \$pdo->setAttribute(PDO::ATTR_ERRMODE, PDO::ERRMODE_EXCEPTION). Use try/catch blocks to handle database errors gracefully. In production, log errors to a file instead of displaying them to users — exposing error details can reveal sensitive information about your database structure.\n\nPassword Security\n\nNever store passwords in plain text. Use password_hash() with PASSWORD_BCRYPT or PASSWORD_ARGON2ID for hashing, and password_verify() for checking passwords. These functions handle salt generation automatically and are resistant to rainbow table attacks.\n\nConnection Management\n\nEstablish a single database connection and reuse it throughout your application. Close connections when they are no longer needed. Use connection pooling in high-traffic applications. Set the character encoding to UTF-8 immediately after connecting: \$pdo->exec('SET NAMES utf8mb4').\n\nDatabase Design\n\nChoose appropriate data types for each column — do not use VARCHAR(255) for everything. Add indexes to columns used in WHERE and JOIN clauses. Use foreign keys to maintain referential integrity. Normalize your schema to reduce redundancy, but denormalize strategically where performance demands it.\n\nTransaction Management\n\nWrap related database operations in transactions to ensure data consistency. If one operation fails, roll back the entire transaction. This is critical for operations like transferring funds, creating orders with multiple items, or any multi-step database update.",
