        "Modern Frontend Development",
        "Modern frontend development has evolved significantly with frameworks, build tools, and new browser APIs. This post explores the tools and techniques that define today's frontend landscape.\n\nThe Modern JavaScript Ecosystem\n\nToday's frontend development revolves around a rich ecosystem of tools and frameworks. Package managers like npm and yarn manage dependencies. Bundlers like Webpack, Vite, and esbuild compile, optimize, and bundle your code. Transpilers like Babel ensure compatibility with older browsers. TypeScript adds static typing for improved developer experience and code reliability.\n\nFrameworks and Libraries\n\nReact, Vue, and Angular dominate the frontend framework landscape. React, developed by Facebook, uses a component-based architecture with a virtual DOM and JSX syntax. Vue offers a gentle learning curve with its template syntax and reactive data binding. Angular provides a comprehensive, opinionated framework with TypeScript, dependency injection, and a powerful CLI.\n\nComponent-Based Architecture\n\nModern frontends are built from reusable components. Each component encapsulates its own HTML structure, CSS styling, and JavaScript logic. This approach promotes code reuse, easier testing, and better maintainability. Component libraries like Material UI, Ant Design, and Tailwind CSS accelerate development by providing pre-built, customizable components.\n\nState Management\n\nAs applications grow, managing state becomes complex. Solutions like Redux, Zustand, Pinia (Vue), and NgRx (Angular) provide centralized state management with predictable data flow. For simpler needs, React's Context API or Vue's provide/inject pattern may suffice.\n\nBuild and Development Tools\n\nVite has emerged as the preferred development server and build tool, offering instant hot module replacement (HMR) and fast builds through native ES modules. ESLint enforces code quality standards, Prettier handles formatting, and Husky runs checks on git commits. CI/CD pipelines automate testing and deployment.\n\nPerformance Optimization\n\nModern frontend performance involves code splitting (loading only the code needed for each page), lazy loading images and components, tree shaking (eliminating unused code), and caching strategies with service workers. Core Web Vitals — LCP, FID, and CLS — are the key metrics to monitor and optimize.\n\nAccessibility (a11y)\n\nBuilding accessible websites is both an ethical responsibility and a legal requirement in many jurisdictions. Use semantic HTML elements, provide alt text for images, ensure keyboard navigation works, maintain sufficient color contrast, and test with screen readers. Tools like axe, Lighthouse, and WAVE help identify accessibility issues.",
