        "Database Normalization Guide",
        "Database normalization is the process of organizing data to reduce redundancy and improve data integrity. Understanding normal forms is essential for designing efficient database schemas.\n\nWhy Normalize?\n\nWithout normalization, databases suffer from anomalies — problems that occur when inserting, updating, or deleting data. For example, in an unnormalized table storing orders with customer information repeated on every row, updating a customer's address requires modifying every row containing that customer. Missing even one row creates inconsistent data.\n\nFirst Normal Form (1NF)\n\n1NF requires that each column contains only atomic (indivisible) values, and each row is unique. A table violates 1NF if it contains repeating groups or multi-valued fields. For example, a 'phone_numbers' column containing '555-1234, 555-5678' violates 1NF. Instead, create a separate phone_numbers table with individual rows for each number.\n\nSecond Normal Form (2NF)\n\n2NF requires that the table is in 1NF and every non-key column depends on the entire primary key, not just part of it. This matters for tables with composite primary keys. For example, in an order_items table with a composite key of (order_id, product_id), if the product_name depends only on product_id, it should be moved to a separate products table.\n\nThird Normal Form (3NF)\n\n3NF requires that the table is in 2NF and no non-key column depends on another non-key column (no transitive dependencies). For example, if an employees table contains department_id and department_name, the department_name depends on department_id, not on the employee. Move department_name to a separate departments table.\n\nBeyond 3NF\n\nBoyce-Codd Normal Form (BCNF), Fourth Normal Form (4NF), and Fifth Normal Form (5NF) address increasingly rare anomalies. In practice, most applications achieve good results with 3NF.\n\nWhen to Denormalize\n\nStrict normalization can lead to many joins, impacting query performance. Strategic denormalization — intentionally duplicating data for read performance — is sometimes necessary. Common techniques include adding computed columns, creating summary tables, and caching frequently joined data. Always start normalized and denormalize only when you have measurable performance issues and have exhausted other optimization options like indexing.",
