        "Responsive Web Design Principles",
        "Responsive web design ensures your website looks great on all devices, from large desktop monitors to mobile phones. This comprehensive guide covers the essential strategies and techniques.\n\nThe Mobile-First Approach\n\nMobile-first design starts with the smallest screen and progressively enhances the layout for larger screens. This approach forces you to prioritize content and functionality, resulting in cleaner, more focused designs. Write your base CSS for mobile, then use min-width media queries to add complexity for tablets and desktops.\n\nMedia Queries\n\nMedia queries are the foundation of responsive design. They allow you to apply CSS rules conditionally based on device characteristics. Common breakpoints target phones (max-width: 599px), tablets (600px-1023px), and desktops (1024px+). However, choose breakpoints based on where your content naturally breaks, not on specific devices.\n\nFlexible Grid Systems\n\nUse relative units like percentages, fr (fractional units), em, and rem instead of fixed pixel values. CSS Grid and Flexbox make creating flexible layouts straightforward. A simple responsive grid: grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr)) creates a layout that automatically adjusts the number of columns based on available space.\n\nFluid Typography\n\nTypography should scale smoothly across screen sizes. The clamp() function is ideal: font-size: clamp(1rem, 2.5vw, 2rem) sets a minimum, preferred, and maximum size. This ensures text is readable on phones without being overwhelming on large screens.\n\nResponsive Images\n\nImages are often the largest assets on a page. Use the srcset attribute to provide multiple image resolutions, letting the browser choose the most appropriate one. The <picture> element enables art direction — serving completely different images based on screen size. Always set max-width: 100% to prevent images from overflowing their containers.\n\nTouch-Friendly Design\n\nMobile users interact through touch, not mouse clicks. Ensure tap targets are at least 44x44 pixels. Add adequate spacing between interactive elements to prevent accidental taps. Consider hover states carefully — they don't exist on touch devices. Use CSS touch-action to control touch behavior and prevent unwanted zooming or scrolling.\n\nTesting Across Devices\n\nUse browser developer tools to simulate various screen sizes and devices. Test on actual devices when possible, as emulators cannot perfectly replicate real-world conditions like network speed, touch responsiveness, and rendering differences. Services like BrowserStack and Sauce Labs provide access to hundreds of real devices.",
