        "AJAX and Fetch API Deep Dive",
        "The Fetch API provides a modern interface for making HTTP requests in JavaScript. It replaces the older XMLHttpRequest with a cleaner, promise-based API that integrates seamlessly with async/await.\n\nThe History of AJAX\n\nAJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) was popularized by Google Maps and Gmail in the mid-2000s, enabling web pages to update content without full page reloads. Originally built on the XMLHttpRequest (XHR) object, AJAX transformed static web pages into dynamic, desktop-like applications. Despite the name, modern AJAX primarily uses JSON instead of XML.\n\nIntroduction to the Fetch API\n\nThe Fetch API, available in all modern browsers, provides a simpler and more powerful way to make HTTP requests. The basic syntax is straightforward: fetch(url) returns a Promise that resolves to a Response object. Unlike XHR, Fetch uses Promises natively, making it integrate perfectly with async/await.\n\nMaking GET Requests\n\nasync function getUsers() {\n  const response = await fetch('/api/users');\n  if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Network response was not ok');\n  const users = await response.json();\n  return users;\n}\n\nAlways check response.ok — Fetch does not reject on HTTP error statuses (404, 500). It only rejects on network failures.\n\nPOST, PUT, and DELETE Requests\n\nSend data by passing an options object to fetch() with method, headers, and body properties. For JSON data: fetch(url, { method: 'POST', headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' }, body: JSON.stringify(data) }). FormData objects can be used for multipart form submissions including file uploads.\n\nHandling Responses\n\nThe Response object provides methods for different data formats: response.json() for JSON data, response.text() for plain text, response.blob() for binary data like images, and response.formData() for form data. Each method returns a Promise.\n\nAdvanced Features\n\nAbortController lets you cancel in-flight requests — essential for search-as-you-type features and component unmounting. The Headers API provides methods to inspect and modify request/response headers. Request and Response can be cloned for advanced caching strategies.\n\nError Handling Patterns\n\nImplement robust error handling by wrapping fetch calls in try/catch blocks. Create a reusable fetch wrapper that handles common scenarios: network errors, HTTP errors, JSON parsing errors, and timeouts. Consider implementing retry logic with exponential backoff for transient failures.",
        "Kate Bishop",
        "JavaScript"
