        "PHP Sessions and Authentication",
        "User authentication is critical for web applications. This comprehensive guide covers implementing secure login systems using PHP sessions, password hashing, and modern security best practices.\n\nUnderstanding HTTP Sessions\n\nHTTP is a stateless protocol — each request is independent with no memory of previous requests. Sessions solve this by assigning each visitor a unique session ID (stored in a cookie) that maps to server-side data. In PHP, call session_start() at the beginning of each page to access session data through the \$_SESSION superglobal array.\n\nHow PHP Sessions Work\n\nWhen session_start() is called, PHP checks for an existing session cookie. If found, it loads the corresponding session data from the server. If not, it creates a new session with a unique ID. Session data persists across page loads until the session expires or is explicitly destroyed.\n\nBuilding a Login System\n\nA secure login system involves several components: a registration form that hashes passwords before storage, a login form that verifies credentials, session management to track authenticated users, and middleware to protect restricted pages.\n\nRegistration — hash the password: \$hash = password_hash(\$password, PASSWORD_BCRYPT); Store only the hash in the database, never the plain text password.\n\nLogin — verify the password: if (password_verify(\$inputPassword, \$storedHash)) { \$_SESSION['user_id'] = \$user['id']; }. Redirect to a dashboard on success or show an error on failure.\n\nSession Security\n\nRegenerate the session ID after login with session_regenerate_id(true) to prevent session fixation attacks. Set secure session cookie parameters: use HttpOnly (prevents JavaScript access), Secure (HTTPS only), and SameSite (prevents CSRF). Configure session.gc_maxlifetime for appropriate session expiration.\n\nProtecting Routes\n\nCreate a middleware function that checks if a user is authenticated before allowing access to protected pages. If \$_SESSION['user_id'] is not set, redirect to the login page. For role-based access, store the user's role in the session and check it before granting access to admin features.\n\nRemember Me Functionality\n\nImplement \"remember me\" with a secure token stored in a long-lived cookie and a corresponding hash in the database. When the session expires, check for the remember-me cookie, validate the token against the database, and restore the session. Always generate a new token after each use to prevent replay attacks.\n\nLogout and Session Cleanup\n\nProper logout requires multiple steps: clear the \$_SESSION array, destroy the session with session_destroy(), and expire the session cookie. If using remember-me tokens, also delete the token from the database.\n\nAdvanced Topics\n\nFor high-traffic applications, consider storing sessions in Redis or Memcached instead of the filesystem. Implement CSRF protection with per-form tokens. Use multi-factor authentication (MFA) for sensitive applications. Rate-limit login attempts to prevent brute-force attacks.",
